acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The classical application of the hypergeometric distribution is <b>sampl=
ing without replacement</b>. Think of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Urn_problem" title=3D"Urn problem">urn</a> with two colors of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marbles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Marbles">marbles</a>, red and green. Define drawing a green marble as a suc=
cess and drawing a red marble as a failure. Let <i>N</i> describe the numbe=
r of <b>all marbles in the urn</b> (see contingency table below) and <i>K</=
i> describe the number of <b>green marbles</b>, then <i>N</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=
=92&nbsp;<i>K</i> corresponds to the number of <b>red marbles</b>. Now, sta=
nding next to the urn, you close your eyes and draw n marbles without repla=
cement. Define <i>X</i> as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rando=
m_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variable</a> whose outcome is =
<i>k</i>, the number of green marbles drawn in the experiment. This situati=
on is illustrated by the following <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Contingency_table" title=3D"Contingency table">contingency table</a>:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"text-align:center">
<tbody><tr>
<th></th>
<th>drawn</th>
<th>not drawn</th>
<th>total
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td align=3D"right"><b>green marbles</b></td>
<td><i>k</i></td>
<td><i>K</i> =E2=88=92 <i>k</i></td>
<td><i>K</i>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td align=3D"right"><b>red marbles</b></td>
<td><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 <i>k</i></td>
<td><i>N + k =E2=88=92 n =E2=88=92 K</i></td>
<td><i>N =E2=88=92 K</i>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td align=3D"right"><b>total</b></td>
<td><i>n</i></td>
<td><i>N =E2=88=92 n</i></td>
<td><i>N</i>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>Indeed, we are interested in calculating the probability of drawing k gr=
een marbles in n draws, given that there are K green marbles out of a total=
 of N marbles. For this example, assume that there are <b>5</b> green and <=
b>45</b> red marbles in the urn. Standing next to the urn, you close your e=
yes and draw <b>10</b> marbles without replacement. What is the probability=
 that exactly <b>4</b> of the <b>10</b> are green?
</p><p>This problem is summarized by the following contingency table:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"text-align:center">

<tbody><tr>
<th></th>
<th>drawn</th>
<th>not drawn</th>
<th>total
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td align=3D"right"><b>green marbles</b>
</td>
<td><i>k</i> =3D <b>4</b>
</td>
<td><i>K</i> =E2=88=92 <i>k</i> =3D <b>1</b>
</td>
<td><i>K</i> =3D <b>5</b>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td align=3D"right"><b>red marbles</b>
</td>
<td><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 <i>k</i> =3D <b>6</b>
</td>
<td><i>N + k =E2=88=92 n =E2=88=92 K</i> =3D <b>39</b>
</td>
<td><i>N =E2=88=92 K</i> =3D <b>45</b>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td align=3D"right"><b>total</b>
</td>
<td><i>n</i> =3D <b>10</b>
</td>
<td><i>N =E2=88=92 n</i> =3D <b>40</b>
</td>
<td><i>N</i> =3D <b>50</b>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>To find the probability of <b>drawing k green marbles in exactly n draws=
 out of N total draws</b>, we identify X as a hyper-geometric random variab=
