data-file-height=3D"1328"></a><figcaption>Samples used for election audits =
and resulting chance of missing a problem</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Election_audits" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Election audits">Election audits</a> typically test a samp=
le of machine-counted precincts to see if recounts by hand or machine match=
 the original counts. Mismatches result in either a report or a larger reco=
unt. The sampling rates are usually defined by law, not statistical design,=
 so for a legally defined sample size <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">n</span>, what is the probability of missing a problem=
 which is present in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">K</span> precincts, such as a hack or bug? This is the probability that=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D 0 .</span> Bugs are often obscure, an=
d a hacker can minimize detection by affecting only a few precincts, which =
will still affect close elections, so a plausible scenario is for <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span> to be on the orde=
r of 5% of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</spa=
n>. Audits typically cover 1% to 10% of precincts (often 3%),<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-newyorkaudit_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Hypergeometric_distribution#cite_note-newyorkaudit-9"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-vvstates_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypergeometric_distribution#cite_note-vvstates-10"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-ncsl_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypergeometric_distribution#cite_note-ncsl-11"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> so they have a high chance of missing a problem. For example, if a =
problem is present in 5 of 100 precincts, a 3% sample has 86% probability t=
hat <span class=3D"nowrap"> <span class=3D"texhtml"> <i>k</i> =3D 0 </span>=
 </span> so the problem would not be noticed, and only 14% probability of t=
he problem appearing in the sample (positive <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;"> k </span>):
</p>
